snippet.textDisplay: How many 'hustlers trading at the bus-stop' do, in fact, 'rise up' socio-economically? Very few, I imagine. Most likely they succumb to addiction, are brutalized, or die. That's why this song doesn't ring as true, as it perhaps could. I'd prefer a more authentic narrative about life as a member of the underclass, where 'the struggle' is seemingly eternal. A glossed up fairytale about individual emancipation only gets me halfway to the truth. Having said this, I love the song and deeply appreciate the socially conscious sentiment.
